	Abstract = {We propose a model of motivated skepticism that helps explain when and why citizens are biased‐information processors. Two experimental studies explore how citizens evaluate arguments about affirmative action and gun control, finding strong evidence of a prior attitude effect such that attitudinally congruent arguments are evaluated as stronger than attitudinally incongruent arguments. When reading pro and con arguments, participants (Ps) counterargue the contrary arguments and uncritically accept supporting arguments, evidence of a disconfirmation bias. We also find a confirmation bias---the seeking out of confirmatory evidence---when Ps are free to self‐select the source of the arguments they read. Both the confirmation and disconfirmation biases lead to attitude polarization---the strengthening of t2 over t1 attitudes---especially among those with the strongest priors and highest levels of political sophistication. We conclude with a discussion of the normative implications of these findings for rational behavior in a democracy.},
	Author = {Charles S. Taber and Milton Lodge},
	Comment = {Takeaways: - Motivated skepticism: people usually accept presented information but begin to question when any contrary evidence is presented. It helps explain when and why there's biased-information process among citizens. - In the normative model, collecting and integrating information should be independent form prior belief. - However, people are more likely to accept/seeking supportive evidence while dismissing contrary evidence to their prior belief. Why? (RQ) - Theory of motivated political reasoning suggests two motives to reasoning : accuracy goal, and partisan goal (the latter usually considered to drive selective information process and affect-driven motivated reasoning) - Prior beliefs and attitudes impact on the evaluation of new information and information updating process : prior attitude effect, disconfirmation bias, and confirmation bias - Conditioning on attitudes strength and sophistication level, disconfirmation bias and confirmation bias lead attitude polarization. attitudes are more lilkey to be strengthening among those with the stronger priors and higher levels of political sophistication. Questions/Comment: - These experiments are about evaluation of argument (info) not really about Ps' own attitude changes - Need to test how credibility of info source affect on changes in their attitudes. Strength of prior attitudes and sophistication may be entangled},
	Doi = {10.1111/j.1540-5907.2006.00214.x},
	File = {:/Users/shinyoungpark/Downloads/Taber(2006)motivated.pdf:PDF},
	Journal = {American Journal of Political Science},
	Number = {3},
