@Misc{clifford2020increasing,
  author   = {Clifford, Scott and Sheagley, Geoffrey and Piston, Spencer},
  note     = {Working Paper},
  title    = {Increasing Precision in Survey Experiments Without Introducing Bias},
  year     = {2020},
  comment  = {overview:
- most common design is the between-subjects design in which outcome is only measured post-treatment -> low precision, requires large sample sizes
- alternative designs that involve repeated mesurement of the DV promise greater precision but are rarely used out of fears that the design may bias treatment effects
- this paper shows results form 6 experiments manipulatign designs and shos that repeated measures designs substantially increase precision while introducing little to no bias
- within-subject designs also offer new insights into heterogeneous treatment effects
- interesting finding: most respondents forget their previous response and believe that their opinions did not change in pretest posttest even if they did
- only caveat: within-subject designs are limited to cases in which the effect of the independent variable can be removed
-> "Given the clear gains in precision and weak evidence for bias, we recommend that
researchers use prepost and within-subjects designs whenever possible."

experimental designs considered in the studies:
- posttest -> standard design
- prepost -> standard design + pre-treatment measure (same item)
- quasi-prepost -> standard design + pre-treatment measure (slightly altered item)
- within -> prepost + treatment before first measurement in control (i.e., every group recieves treatment, only ordering of treatments and measurements is varied)

potential sources for bias in repeated measures designs:
- demand effects -> little empirical evidence
- consistency pressures -> limited by subject's memory
- interaction between testing and the treatment -> little evidence?

comments / questions:
- paper also includes some useful discussion regarding the inclusion of covariates to increase precision (which it does, but the benefits are smaller than repeated measurement designs)
